Plum Blossom Stage
London — A daunting task lies before the newly appointed British Prime Minister, Theresa May: to carry out the demand of British voters — or more precisely, voters in England and Wales — to "leave the European Union" and manage the significant consequences that this entails.
The challenge she faces is far more daunting than that of any previous prime minister in recent years.
But she might be capable of completing this task.
No one should underestimate Mei.
Like German Chancellor Merkel, who has demonstrated courage in a series of crises, all the tools necessary to complete the task are in May's hands.
She is smart and resilient, with no patience for nonsense.
She has a strong sense of public service and equally strong values.
She is not bound by any ideology, is very skilled at maintaining control, and operates within self-defined boundaries to ensure familiarity with the issues she handles.
Mei won most of the battles she participated in and showed no mercy to those who had used underhanded tactics against her.
But she had few enemies within the party and was quite popular among ordinary party members.
This is a powerful combination — she needs to make full use of it to lead the UK's Brexit process.
The Brexit process has already started, and there is no doubt about that.
Even if Scotland and Northern Ireland voted to remain in the EU, May repeatedly stated that the Brexit referendum could not be reversed.
She repeatedly emphasized that "Brexit is Brexit," and her senior ministers all agreed with her view.
But May has not yet given an exact definition of Brexit.
This task is extremely difficult to complete.
Imagine someone telling you, "Breakfast is just breakfast," and then starting to prepare your food.
It's hard for you to clearly know what you will actually eat.
A Northern Irish "Ulster fry" — eggs, bacon, pork sausages, black pudding, potato, soda bread, and fried tomato — with a cup of tea?
Coffee and pastries?
Depending on your environment and personal preferences, you may feel very different about various possible combinations.
The same situation applies to Brexit.
Some people may primarily focus on preventing the flow of EU labor into the UK.
Some people are more concerned about obtaining access to a single market.
But unlike breakfast, the UK cannot order one of each dish on the menu.
A reality often overlooked by Brexit supporters is that the EU will not give Britain benefits for free.
This is not because EU leaders want to win favor or punish Britain for rejecting the EU (sometimes such provocative rhetoric becomes prevalent, such as the newly appointed British Foreign Secretary Boris Johnson's claim of "Hitlerian imperialism").
In contrast, we British often forget that everyone—including the EU and all its member states—has their own political or commercial interests that they have vowed to protect.
For May, the core challenge in the coming months will be to determine, on a realistic basis, what Britain's objectives should be after the difficult negotiations on the relationship with the EU (and in the trade area, the relationship with the world) have begun.
Given the scope of the agenda (I can think of at least six major topics that would need separate negotiations), the negotiation process may take several years to complete.
By the time the negotiations are completed, my granddaughter, who is 11 years old, may have already started university!
We must clarify the key points to prevent the negotiation from dragging on longer.
The objective is certainly to strike a balance between enabling UK-exported goods and services (particularly financial services) to enter other European countries and limiting the movement of EU citizens into the UK.
The more a negotiator gains in one area, the greater the concessions they need to make in other areas.
Mei needs to fully utilize the knowledge, skills, and political capital she has mastered to ensure the rationality of the negotiation deal.
But even if she could successfully achieve her goals, she would still find that the people dissatisfied are not just a certain part of them — this outcome is inevitable — but all of them.
This will exacerbate another major challenge facing the May government: bridging the growing divide in British society exposed by Brexit.
The working-class voters in northern and central England were the main driving force behind the Brexit referendum. For years, they have felt distant from political leaders, been left behind by globalization, and been marginalized by the supposed representatives of globalization — the European Union.
English metropolitan areas — especially London — may have benefited greatly from globalization, but they have not actually gained anything.
Many members of the working-class community eventually became victims of Brexit populist promises due to a lack of confidence in the Labour Party led by the leftist leader Jeremy Corbyn.
"They called it 'reversing globalization.'"
"We will drive out immigrant workers who suppress wages and divert hundreds of millions of pounds that were originally allocated to the EU into public services."
They promised that Brexit would allow the UK to return to a safer, more prosperous past.
Brexiteers cannot truly fulfill these promises.
Globalization cannot be reversed, just as it is impossible to cut off migration from the European Union.
Any such measures would destroy British businesses.
Even if the economic downturn leads to a decrease in immigration, those workers who voted for Brexit may still be disheartened to find that low-paying jobs remain low-paying and that public services continue to be under heavy strain.
This is unlikely to lead to an increase in social cohesion.
The Brexit referendum has already ignited a difficult-to-control storm of populist sentiment.
Just as Donald Trump was powerless to improve the situation of working-class voters in the United States, the Brexit referendum could not possibly bring benefits to those who chose it, no matter how the circumstances seemed.
Although it has many advantages, such challenges may still be insurmountable.
